(13, 'togaf_preliminary', 'architecture_team', 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase - Prelim_Phase_Architecture & Governance', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase Architecture & Governance KPIs — MiraTV (PROVISIONAL ? CANON CANDIDATE) Purpose This document defines architecture-level and governance-level KPIs used to measure the health, reliability, and integrity of the MiraTV platform. These KPIs support architectural governance , not marketing or field operations. 1? ? Architecture Integrity KPIs Pipeline Completion Rate Definition: Percentage of ingest jobs completing without manual intervention Target: ? 95% Signal Source: Ops DB / job_runs Grinder Failure Transparency Rate Definition: Percentage of failures correctly surfaced and quarantined (not silently bypassed) Target: 100% Rationale: Hidden success is worse than visible failure Partial Truth Acceptance Rate Definition: Percentage of records accepted with explicit unknown fields instead of forced completion Target: Increasing over time Rationale: Measures truth preservation maturity 2? ? Data Integrity KPIs Provenance Coverage Definition: Percentage of records with traceable source and processing history Target: ? 99% Constraint Violation Rate Definition: Number of rejected DB writes due to constraint enforcement Target: Non-zero (expected) Interpretation: Zero indicates missing constraints 3? ? Governance KPIs Canon Rule Violation Rate Definition: Attempts blocked by active governance rules Target: Measured, not minimized Purpose: Detects pressure against governance Provisional Rule Stability Definition: Confidence trend of provisional rules over time Target: Clear convergence or elimination Source: IGM attestation ledger Human Override Frequency Definition: Rate of human overrides of system or AI proposals Target: Declining but never zero Interpretation: Indicates governance maturity, not failure 4? ? AI Safety KPIs AI Proposal Acceptance Rate Definition: Percentage of AI proposals accepted by humans Target: 40–70% Rationale: Too high = rubber stamp, too low = noise AI Boundary Violations Definition: Attempts by AI to exceed permitted scope or agency Target: 0 Severity: Critical incident if >0 5? ? KPI Governance KPIs are reviewed during: ADM Phase A (Vision Validation) Phase G (Architecture Governance) Phase H (Change Management) KPIs inform roadmap adjustments but never override canon rules Status Declaration This KPI set is architecture-scoped and governance-aligned. Business and marketing KPIs are maintained separately and do not influence architectural enforcement. Status: PROVISIONAL (eligible for canon after sustained use)', '2026-01-29 14:35:37'),
(14, 'togaf_preliminary', 'architecture_team', 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase - Prelim_Phase_Architecture_Maturity_Mir', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase Architecture Maturity Assessment — MiraTV Purpose This document defines the current and target maturity levels of the MiraTV enterprise architecture capability. It establishes a baseline for organizational readiness and provides direction for governance, tooling, process, and alignment improvements across the TOGAF ADM lifecycle. 1. Architecture Maturity Assessment Governance: Current Maturity: Low Target Maturity: Medium Tools: Current Maturity: Ad-hoc Target Maturity: Standardized Processes: Current Maturity: Informal Target Maturity: Defined and repeatable Documentation: Current Maturity: Minimal Target Maturity: Formal and traceable Alignment with Business: Current Maturity: Moderate Target Maturity: Strong and ongoing 2. Maturity Interpretation Governance will evolve from founder-led decision-making to lightweight, documented architecture oversight. Tools will move from pragmatic selection to standardized usage. Processes will mature from informal practices to repeatable workflows aligned to TOGAF ADM and Agile methods. Documentation will become versioned and traceable. Business alignment will strengthen through continuous linkage between strategy and architecture decisions. 3. TOGAF Alignment This maturity assessment supports the Preliminary Phase, Phase A (Architecture Vision), and Phase H (Architecture Change Management). Maturity targets will be reviewed at the start of each ADM cycle and adjusted as needed. Status Declaration This document is the official Architecture Maturity Assessment for MiraTV under the TOGAF Preliminary Phase and establishes the baseline for continuous improvement.', '2026-01-29 14:35:38'),
(15, 'togaf_preliminary', 'architecture_team', 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase - Prelim_Phase_Architecture_Principles_M', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase Architecture Principles — MiraTV (CANON) Purpose This document defines the binding Architecture Principles that govern all enterprise architecture decisions for MiraTV . These principles are enforceable , non-negotiable , and apply across all TOGAF ADM phases. Principle 1: Truth Before Convenience Statement System truth, data integrity, provenance, and governance constraints must never be compromised for convenience, speed, customer experience, or perceived completeness. Rationale MiraTV operates in an environment of unreliable providers and inconsistent external data. Preserving truth — including partial truth and unknowns — is foundational to system reliability, auditability, and long-term intelligence. Implications Data must never be invented, inferred silently, or auto-corrected Partial or unknown data is acceptable and preferred over false completeness User experience must adapt to system truth, not override it AI systems must preserve uncertainty explicitly Principle 2: Database as Authority Statement The database is the authoritative system of record for all operational, architectural, and governance truth. Rationale Only a constrained, auditable persistence layer can preserve provenance, enforce integrity, and enable reliable automation. Implications No component (including AI) may bypass database constraints No system may treat cached, inferred, or computed data as authoritative All writes must be explicit, parameterized, and logged Principle 3: Automation First Statement All operational processes must be automatable, schedulable, and repeatable. Rationale Manual processes do not scale and cannot be governed reliably. Implications Processes must be scriptable and observable Human intervention is escalation, not normal flow Automation failures are signals, not exceptions Principle 4: Governance Over Optimization Statement Architectural governance takes precedence over performance optimization, cost reduction, and implementation convenience. Rationale Optimizations that bypass governance introduce silent risk and long-term instability. Implications Governance rules may block otherwise “efficient” solutions Performance tuning must occur within defined constraints No optimization may bypass provenance or audit requirements Principle 5: AI Without Agency Statement AI systems may observe, analyze, explain, and propose — but may not decide, enforce, or act autonomously. Rationale Separating intelligence from agency preserves safety, auditability, and human authority. Implications AI may never write directly to production databases AI may never promote rules to canon AI outputs are advisory unless explicitly approved by human authority Principle 6: Reuse With Provenance Statement Reuse is encouraged only when provenance, scope, and governance boundaries are preserved. Rationale Reuse without provenance spreads hidden error and invalid assumptions. Implications Shared components must expose context and constraints Reuse must not bypass validation or governance Duplication is acceptable when reuse violates integrity Governance Statement These principles are enforcing canon . Exceptions require explicit Architecture Board approval and documented rationale. Status Declaration This document is the official Architecture Principles canon for MiraTV under the TOGAF Preliminary Phase.', '2026-01-29 14:35:38'),
(16, 'togaf_preliminary', 'architecture_team', 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase - Prelim_Phase_Architecture_Vision_Brief', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase Architecture Vision Brief — MiraTV Purpose This Architecture Vision Brief outlines the foundational context and strategic intent for initiating the MiraTV enterprise architecture. It defines business drivers, scope, constraints, stakeholders, and guiding principles to ensure alignment with business objectives and readiness for the TOGAF ADM lifecycle. Architecture Vision Transform MiraTV into a sovereign, automation-first IPTV platform that reliably ingests, normalizes, and delivers Live TV, VOD, Series, and EPG content through a scalable, secure, and provider-independent architecture capable of future AI-assisted operations. Business Context MiraTV operates in the IPTV and digital media distribution domain, characterized by fragmented providers, unreliable data formats, and high-volume ingest requirements. The platform centralizes and governs external content into a single authoritative catalog. Architecture Project Sponsor Sponsor: Founder / Platform Architect — MiraTV Mandate: Deliver a secure, resilient, and scalable platform that enables automation, provider independence, and long-term platform sovereignty. Business Drivers - Growth of IPTV and alternative content delivery platforms - Provider unreliability and lack of standards compliance - Need for automated, schedulable ingest pipelines - Cost efficiency using lightweight infrastructure - Future AI-assisted operational intelligence Scope In Scope: - Business, Data, Application, and Technology Architectures - Live TV, VOD, Series, and EPG ingest pipelines - Automation, orchestration, and security controls Out of Scope: - Frontend UI and player UX - Billing, entitlement, and recommendation engines - Deep AI/ML model training Constraints - Budget and infrastructure limitations - Provider latency and instability - Shared hosting environments - Time-to-market pressures - Security and compliance requirements Assumptions - Providers will remain unreliable - Architecture must tolerate failure as data - MySQL remains the authoritative system of record - Automation and AI will be layered incrementally Key Stakeholders - Founder / Platform Architect - Operations and Engineering leadership - Content partners - End users Readiness Assessment Architecture capability, governance, tooling, and baseline architecture are established. The organization is approved to proceed into detailed architecture development phases. Next Steps - Approve Architecture Vision - Document Baseline Architecture (Phases B–D) - Define Target Architecture - Establish Transition Architectures Status Declaration This document is the official Architecture Vision Brief for MiraTV under the TOGAF Preliminary Phase and authorizes progression into ADM Phase A execution.', '2026-01-29 14:35:39'),
(17, 'togaf_preliminary', 'architecture_team', 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase - Prelim_Phase_Defined_Architecture_Prin', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase Architecture Principles — MiraTV (CANON) Purpose This document defines the binding Architecture Principles that govern all enterprise architecture decisions for MiraTV . These principles are enforceable , non-negotiable , and apply across all TOGAF ADM phases. Principle 1: Truth Before Convenience Statement System truth, data integrity, provenance, and governance constraints must never be compromised for convenience, speed, customer experience, or perceived completeness. Rationale MiraTV operates in an environment of unreliable providers and inconsistent external data. Preserving truth — including partial truth and unknowns — is foundational to system reliability, auditability, and long-term intelligence. Implications Data must never be invented, inferred silently, or auto-corrected Partial or unknown data is acceptable and preferred over false completeness User experience must adapt to system truth, not override it AI systems must preserve uncertainty explicitly Principle 2: Database as Authority Statement The database is the authoritative system of record for all operational, architectural, and governance truth. Rationale Only a constrained, auditable persistence layer can preserve provenance, enforce integrity, and enable reliable automation. Implications No component (including AI) may bypass database constraints No system may treat cached, inferred, or computed data as authoritative All writes must be explicit, parameterized, and logged Principle 3: Automation First Statement All operational processes must be automatable, schedulable, and repeatable. Rationale Manual processes do not scale and cannot be governed reliably. Implications Processes must be scriptable and observable Human intervention is escalation, not normal flow Automation failures are signals, not exceptions Principle 4: Governance Over Optimization Statement Architectural governance takes precedence over performance optimization, cost reduction, and implementation convenience. Rationale Optimizations that bypass governance introduce silent risk and long-term instability. Implications Governance rules may block otherwise “efficient” solutions Performance tuning must occur within defined constraints No optimization may bypass provenance or audit requirements Principle 5: AI Without Agency Statement AI systems may observe, analyze, explain, and propose — but may not decide, enforce, or act autonomously. Rationale Separating intelligence from agency preserves safety, auditability, and human authority. Implications AI may never write directly to production databases AI may never promote rules to canon AI outputs are advisory unless explicitly approved by human authority Principle 6: Reuse With Provenance Statement Reuse is encouraged only when provenance, scope, and governance boundaries are preserved. Rationale Reuse without provenance spreads hidden error and invalid assumptions. Implications Shared components must expose context and constraints Reuse must not bypass validation or governance Duplication is acceptable when reuse violates integrity Governance Statement These principles are enforcing canon . Exceptions require explicit Architecture Board approval and documented rationale. Status Declaration This document is the official Architecture Principles canon for MiraTV under the TOGAF Preliminary Phase.', '2026-01-29 14:35:40'),
(18, 'togaf_preliminary', 'architecture_team', 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase - Prelim_Phase_Establish_Architecture_Ca', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase Establish Architecture Capability — MiraTV Purpose This document establishes the Enterprise Architecture Capability for MiraTV. It defines sponsorship, governance structures, roles, responsibilities, and tools required to ensure architecture work is authorized, governed, repeatable, and aligned with strategic objectives. This capability is a mandatory outcome of the TOGAF Preliminary Phase. 1. Architecture Capability Components Architecture Sponsor: CEO / Founder of MiraTV. Provides executive sponsorship, sets strategic direction, approves architecture priorities, and resolves escalated decisions. Architecture Board: Lightweight governance body composed of advisors and senior roles (e.g., Operations, IT, Marketing). Responsible for principle approval, scope alignment, and governance oversight. Architecture Team: Initially small and founder-led, supported by external consultants or part-time specialists as required. Governance Framework: Lightweight IT governance appropriate for early-stage growth, designed to scale. May align with ITIL practices as operational maturity increases. Architecture Tools: ArchiMate-compatible tools such as Archi or BizzDesign, supplemented by Miro / Draw.io and AI-assisted modeling tools for early-stage exploration. 2. Architecture Role Assignments Architecture Sponsor: Korcel Price Architecture Board: Advisors (as engaged) Architecture Team: Korcel Price Governance Framework Owner: Architecture Sponsor Architecture Tooling Owner: Architecture Team 3. Governance Model Statement MiraTV employs lightweight architecture governance emphasizing clear principles, fast decision-making, and documented rationale. Governance will mature alongside organizational growth without invalidating earlier architectural decisions. 4. Tooling Strategy Statement Architecture tools are selected to enable—not constrain—architecture work. Formal ArchiMate modeling is used where rigor is required, while visual and AI-assisted tools support rapid ideation and documentation. All tools remain replaceable. Status Declaration This document is the official Establish Architecture Capability artifact for MiraTV under the TOGAF Preliminary Phase.', '2026-01-29 14:35:41'),
(19, 'togaf_preliminary', 'architecture_team', 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase - Prelim_Phase_KPIs_MiraTV', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) — MiraTV Purpose This document defines the Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) used to measure the success of the MiraTV enterprise architecture in delivering business value, operational efficiency, and digital platform effectiveness. These KPIs provide objective success criteria and support architecture governance across the TOGAF ADM lifecycle. 1. Business KPIs Monthly Recurring Revenue (MRR): Revenue from repeat customers Target: $10,000 per month by Month 12 Customer Acquisition Cost (CAC): Average cost to acquire one customer Target: Less than $50 Customer Lifetime Value (CLTV): Total value generated from one customer Target: Greater than $300 Churn Rate: Percentage of customers who stop using services Target: Less than 10% monthly Net Promoter Score (NPS): Customer satisfaction and loyalty indicator Target: Greater than 50 2. Operational KPIs First-Time Fix Rate: Percentage of jobs resolved on first visit Target: Greater than 85% Average Response Time: Time to acknowledge a service request Target: Less than 2 hours Job Completion Time: Average time to complete a task Target: Less than 1.5 hours Technician Utilization: Percentage of billable technician time Target: Greater than 75% 3. Digital Engagement KPIs App Downloads / Active Users: Adoption of the MiraTV application Target: 5,000 or more installs Website Conversion Rate: Percentage of visitors converted to active users Target: Greater than 7% Email Open Rate: Percentage of marketing emails opened Target: Greater than 25% Social Engagement Rate: Interaction on posts and campaigns Target: Greater than 5% 4. KPI Governance and TOGAF Alignment KPIs will be reviewed during Phase A (Architecture Vision), Phase G (Architecture Governance), and Phase H (Architecture Change Management). Performance against these KPIs will inform architecture roadmap updates, investment prioritization, and continuous improvement initiatives. Status Declaration This document is the official Preliminary Phase KPI artifact for MiraTV and is approved for use across the TOGAF ADM lifecycle.', '2026-01-29 14:35:41'),
(20, 'togaf_preliminary', 'architecture_team', 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase - Prelim_Phase_Request_for_Architecture_', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase Request for Architecture Work — MiraTV Purpose This document formally establishes the Request for Architecture Work for the MiraTV platform. It authorizes the initiation of ADM Phase A: Architecture Vision and defines the intended outcomes, scope, constraints, stakeholders, and timeframe for the architecture effort. 1. Architecture Work Trigger The request for architecture work is triggered by the need to formalize MiraTV’s existing production architecture, align platform evolution with long-term strategy, and establish clear architectural direction to guide future investment and delivery. 2. Intended Outcomes The Architecture Vision is expected to deliver: - Clear articulation of business objectives and success criteria - High-level summary of the Baseline Architecture - High-level description of the Target Architecture - Identification of key stakeholders and concerns - Definition of architectural constraints and assumptions - A roadmap framing for subsequent ADM phases 3. Scope of Architecture Work The Architecture Vision will address enterprise-wide scope across Business, Data, Application, and Technology architectures. Core systems include content ingest pipelines, automation and orchestration, data stores, and security controls. 4. Constraints and Considerations Architecture work must consider budget limitations, provider unreliability, shared hosting environments, time-to-market pressures, and security and compliance requirements. 5. Stakeholders Stakeholders engaged in this architecture work include the Founder / Platform Architect, Operations and Engineering leadership, platform users and partners, and external advisors as applicable. 6. Timeframe The Architecture Vision will be developed within a short, focused timeframe sufficient to capture strategic intent, validate architectural direction, and inform subsequent ADM phases. 7. Authorization Statement This Request for Architecture Work formally authorizes the commencement of TOGAF ADM Phase A: Architecture Vision for MiraTV. All work will adhere to established principles, scope, and governance. Status Declaration This document is the official Request for Architecture Work under the TOGAF Preliminary Phase for MiraTV.', '2026-01-29 14:35:42'),
(21, 'togaf_preliminary', 'architecture_team', 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase - Prelim_Phase_Scope_of_Enterprise_Archi', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase Scope of Enterprise Architecture — MiraTV Purpose This document defines the organizational, geographic, architectural, and system scope of the MiraTV enterprise architecture initiative. Clear scope boundaries ensure focus, effective governance, and alignment with platform strategy throughout the TOGAF ADM lifecycle. 1. Organization Scope MiraTV, including content ingestion operations, data normalization pipelines, platform engineering, operations, and supporting IT functions. 2. Geographic Scope Initial deployment within a single operational region, with architecture explicitly designed to scale nationally and internationally without structural rework. 3. Architecture Domains The enterprise architecture scope includes the following TOGAF domains: - Business Architecture - Data Architecture - Application Architecture - Technology Architecture 4. Enterprise Systems in Scope Core systems governed by this architecture include: - Content ingest pipelines (Live, VOD, Series, EPG) - Orchestration scripts and schedulers - Token-protected PHP ingest services - MySQL content catalog and operational databases - Supporting monitoring and automation tooling 5. Scope Governance Statement This scope applies to all architecture work performed under the TOGAF ADM. Scope will be reviewed and adjusted at the start of each ADM cycle to ensure continued alignment with business objectives and platform evolution.', '2026-01-29 14:35:43'),
(22, 'togaf_preliminary', 'architecture_team', 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase - Prelim_Phase_Stakeholders_MiraTV', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase Stakeholder Definition — MiraTV Purpose This document identifies and analyzes the key stakeholders involved in the MiraTV enterprise architecture initiative. It supports governance, communication planning, and decision-making throughout the TOGAF ADM lifecycle. 1. Stakeholder Catalog Founder / CEO: Strategic direction, investment decisions, platform vision (High Influence) Operations Manager: Scheduling, workforce management, quality control (High Influence) Field Technicians / Partners: Service delivery and customer interaction (Medium Influence) Customers / End Users: Consumers of MiraTV services and platform outputs (High Influence) Customer Support: Handles inquiries, complaints, and feedback (Medium Influence) Technology Lead / Developer: Platform build, integrations, and technical feasibility (High Influence) Marketing & Sales: Customer acquisition, retention, and brand strategy (Medium Influence) Legal / Compliance Consultant: Ensures data privacy and regulatory compliance (Medium Influence) External Advisors / Investors: Strategic guidance and funding alignment (Medium Influence) 2. Stakeholder Assignment Founder / CEO: Korcel Price Operations Manager: Olga Price Field Technicians / Partners: Mina / Jeffrey Customers / End Users: MiraTV users Customer Support: Korcel Price Technology Lead / Developer: Korcel Price Marketing & Sales: To be hired Legal / Compliance Consultant: To be engaged External Advisors / Investors: To be engaged 3. Stakeholder Influence Analysis High Influence Stakeholders: - Founder / CEO - Operations Manager - Technology Lead / Developer - Customers / End Users Medium Influence Stakeholders: - Field Technicians / Partners - Customer Support - Marketing & Sales - Legal / Compliance - External Advisors / Investors 4. TOGAF Alignment This stakeholder definition supports the Preliminary Phase and Phase A of the TOGAF ADM. Stakeholders will be revisited and updated at the start of each ADM cycle. Status Declaration This document is the official Preliminary Phase Stakeholder artifact for MiraTV.', '2026-01-29 14:35:44'),
(23, 'togaf_preliminary', 'architecture_team', 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase - Prelim_Phase_Tools_MiraTV', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase Architecture Tools & Platform Enablement — MiraTV Purpose This document defines the initial tools and platforms that enable MiraTV’s enterprise architecture capability during early growth. Tooling choices prioritize speed to value, low cost, interoperability, and alignment with TOGAF and Agile practices. 1. Architecture Modeling & Design Architecture Modeling Tools: - ArchiMate (via Archi or BizzDesign) - Draw.io for early-stage collaborative modeling Rationale: ArchiMate provides TOGAF-aligned modeling rigor, while Draw.io enables rapid early design. 2. Project & Work Management Recommended Tools: - Trello - ClickUp - Notion - Asana Rationale: Lightweight tools supporting Agile delivery, transparency, and cross-functional collaboration. 3. Core Business Systems CRM & Scheduling: - Zoho CRM - Housecall Pro - Jobber Finance & Invoicing: - QuickBooks - Wave - FreshBooks Rationale: Field-service and SMB-focused platforms with API support and scalability. 4. Application Development Platforms Mobile & Web Development: - Flutter - React Native - Firebase (MVP backend) Backend & Cloud Services: - AWS - Azure - Google Cloud Platform Rationale: Cross-platform development with cloud-neutral backend options to avoid early lock-in. 5. Customer Experience & Feedback Customer Feedback Tools: - Typeform - Google Forms - Intercom Marketing Automation: - Mailchimp - HubSpot (free tier) - Meta Ads Manager Rationale: Supports early-stage customer insight, engagement, and demand generation. 6. Cloud Infrastructure & DevOps Source Control & CI/CD: - GitHub - GitHub Actions Cloud Infrastructure: - AWS / Azure / GCP (core services) Rationale: Enables automation, repeatable deployments, and infrastructure scalability. 7. TOGAF Alignment Statement The tools defined in this document support—but do not define—the MiraTV architecture. All tools are replaceable without violating architecture principles and will be reviewed during subsequent ADM phases as the platform matures.', '2026-01-29 14:35:45'),
(24, 'togaf_preliminary', 'architecture_team', 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase - TOGAF_Preliminary_Phase_MiraTV', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TOGAF Preliminary Phase Enterprise Architecture Definition — MiraTV Objective Establish the architectural framework, principles, scope, and governance structures required to support MiraTV’s growth, platform sovereignty, and digital content strategy. 1. Establish Architecture Capability Architecture Sponsor: Founder / Platform Architect — provides strategic direction and final architectural authority. Architecture Board: Lightweight governance body including Operations, Engineering, and Platform Strategy roles. Architecture Team: Initially founder-led with selective external or part-time specialists. Governance Framework: Lightweight governance aligned to TOGAF, with optional future alignment to ITIL or COBIT. Architecture Tools: ArchiMate-compatible tools such as Draw.io, Miro, or BizzDesign for early modeling. 2. Architecture Principles Provider Independence – Architecture must not rely on provider reliability. Push, Never Pull – Ingest is externally initiated only. Database as Authority – MySQL is the system of record. Security by Design – Token-based access and least privilege enforced. Automation First – All processes must be schedulable and repeatable. 3. Scope of Enterprise Architecture Organization: MiraTV platform operations, ingest, normalization, and catalog management. Geography: Initially single-region hosting, designed for global scalability. Architecture Domains: Business, Data, Application, Technology. Enterprise Systems: Content ingest pipelines, orchestration scripts, PHP ingest endpoints, MySQL catalog. 4. Architecture Framework Primary Framework: TOGAF ADM Supporting Practices: ArchiMate for modeling ITIL for service alignment Agile/Lean for iterative delivery 5. Architecture Maturity Assessment Governance: Low ? Medium Tools: Ad-hoc ? Standardized Processes: Informal ? Repeatable Documentation: Minimal ? Formal Business Alignment: Moderate ? Strong 6. Request for Architecture Work This Preliminary Phase authorizes the initiation of ADM Phase A: Architecture Vision to define baseline and target architectures for MiraTV. Status Declaration This document is the official TOGAF Preliminary Phase deliverable for MiraTV.', '2026-01-29 14:35:45'),
